caption: A place like others in Paris

Time of visit: second half of March 2014. The largest fountain built during Napoleon's reign that still exists. This monumental fountain served to provide fresh drinking water to the population of the neighborhood.
The Palmierulu Fountain was built in 1808, at the initiative of Napoleon I, to commemorate his victories and to offer Parisians free water.

Napoleon ordered the construction of fifteen drinking water fountains in 1806 to improve the water supply of Parisians. The Palm Spring or Victory Spring also commemorates Napoleon's campaign in Egypt, with the sphinx-shaped gargoyles at its base and palm leaves decorating the column. The column is reminiscent of the Roman victory columns in all its elements. It was handed over in 1808.
